Not to be confused with [5th Parliament of the United Kingdom](/5th_Parliament_of_the_United_Kingdom). For those who might mistake one tedious assembly for another.

# 5th Parliament of Great Britain

&#8592; [4th](/4th_Parliament_of_Great_Britain) [6th](/6th_Parliament_of_Great_Britain) &#8594;

A rather telling [portrait of Spencer Compton](/Portrait_of_Spencer_Compton) by [Godfrey Kneller](/Godfrey_Kneller). Compton, ever the dutiful figure, served as the [Speaker of the House of Commons](/Speaker_of_the_House_of_Commons_(United_Kingdom)) during this period. One can almost see the weight of parliamentary procedure etched into his expression.

## Overview

The [5th Parliament of Great Britain](/Parliament_of_Great_Britain) convened during a period of considerable political flux and, for all its grand pronouncements, largely solidified the Whig ascendancy that would define the era. Its term spanned a rather significant seven years, precisely from **17 March 1715** to **10 March 1722**, a duration itself a testament to one of its most defining legislative acts.

### Government

The political landscape of this Parliament was unequivocally **Whig dominated**. This wasn't merely a preference; it was a near-absolute ideological grip on power, a direct consequence of the recent Hanoverian succession and the Whigs' unwavering support for [George I](/George_I_of_Great_Britain). The Tories, unfortunately for them, found themselves in the historical wilderness, tainted by associations with the recently deposed Stuarts and the specter of Jacobitism.

### House of Commons

The lower house, the [House of Commons of Great Britain](/House_of_Commons_of_Great_Britain), was composed of **558 Members of Parliament (MPs)**. A formidable number, one might think, though the actual efficacy of such a crowd often remains debatable.

#### Speaker of the House of Commons

Presiding over this assembly was [Spencer Compton, 1st Earl of Wilmington](/Spencer_Compton,_1st_Earl_of_Wilmington). As [Speaker of the House of Commons](/Speaker_of_the_House_of_Commons_(United_Kingdom)), Compton was a Whig stalwart, a safe pair of hands chosen to guide the proceedings. His tenure was marked by a steady, if not particularly dynamic, adherence to procedure, a necessary quality when navigating the often turbulent waters of early 18th-century British politics.

### House of Lords

The venerable [House of Lords](/House_of_Lords) also played its part, naturally.

#### Leader of the House of Lords

The principal figure leading the government's agenda within the [House of Lords](/House_of_Lords) was **[Viscount Townshend](/Charles_Townshend,_2nd_Viscount_Townshend)**. A politician of considerable weight and influence, Townshend was instrumental in shaping the early Hanoverian government's direction, often acting as a key ministerial spokesman.

### Sessions

This Parliament, in its seven-year span, endured (or perhaps facilitated) a total of eight distinct sessions:

*   **1st Session:** 17 March 1715 – 26 June 1716. This inaugural session set the stage, immediately grappling with the aftermath of the Hanoverian succession and the Jacobite threat.
*   **2nd Session:** 20 February 1717 – 15 July 1717.
*   **3rd Session:** 21 November 1717 – 21 March 1718.
*   **4th Session:** 11 November 1718 – 18 April 1719.
*   **5th Session:** 23 November 1719 – 11 June 1720.
*   **6th Session:** 8 December 1720 – 29 July 1721. A session notably overshadowed by the fallout from the [South Sea Bubble](/South_Sea_Bubble).
*   **7th Session:** 31 July 1721 – 10 August 1721. A brief, perhaps perfunctory, gathering.
*   **8th Session:** 19 October 1721 – 7 March 1722. The final stretch before dissolution, likely dealing with the residual chaos and clean-up operations.

