The [5th Parliament of Great Britain](/Parliament_of_Great_Britain) was officially summoned by [George I of Great Britain](/George_I_of_Great_Britain) on 17 January 1715, a mere formality after the [1715 British general election](/1715_British_general_election) had already determined its composition. It then dutifully assembled on 17 March 1715. Its dissolution on 10 March 1722 marked a significant milestone, as it had been the first Parliament to serve a full term under the provisions of the [Septennial Act 1716](/Septennial_Act_1716). This act, which extended the maximum duration of a parliament from three years to seven, was a deliberate move to ensure political stability in a volatile post-succession landscape, effectively insulating the Whig government from the whims of a potentially fickle electorate for a longer period. A rather convenient piece of legislation, wouldn't you say, for the party in power?

## Composition and Speaker of the House

The [1715 British general election](/1715_British_general_election) delivered a resounding, almost embarrassing, victory for the Whigs. The composition of the new [House of Commons](/House_of_Commons_of_Great_Britain) represented a massive Whig landslide, a stark reversal of the pro-Tory dominance seen in the previous election. The numbers tell a clear story: 341 Whigs against a mere 217 Tories. This overwhelming majority meant that the Whigs could, for all intents and purposes, govern with little effective opposition, a situation that often leads to both decisive action and, inevitably, internal squabbles.

Given this political climate, the installation of [Spencer Compton, 1st Earl of Wilmington](/Spencer_Compton,_1st_Earl_of_Wilmington), as [Speaker of the House of Commons](/Speaker_of_the_House_of_Commons_(United_Kingdom)) was entirely predictable. Compton, a loyal Whig member representing [Sussex](/Sussex_(UK_Parliament_constituency)), was precisely the kind of reliable figure the triumphant party needed to ensure smooth, if somewhat partisan, parliamentary operations. His role was less about impartial arbitration and more about facilitating the government's agenda, a common enough practice then, as now.

## Domination of Whigs under Townshend, Stanhope, and Walpole

The administration of [George I](/George_I_of_Great_Britain), fresh on the throne and still grappling with the unfamiliarity of his new kingdom and language, leaned heavily on the Whigs. This wasn't merely a political alliance but a matter of necessity; the Whigs were the party that had unequivocally championed his accession, effectively securing the Hanoverian dynasty against lingering Jacobite threats. Consequently, they enjoyed the full, though sometimes strained, support of the [House of Commons](/House_of_Commons_of_Great_Britain) and the King himself.

Within this burgeoning Whig power structure, **[Viscount Townshend](/Charles_Townshend,_2nd_Viscount_Townshend)** rapidly emerged as a key figure. Holding the influential post of [Secretary of State for the Northern Department](/Secretary_of_State_for_the_Northern_Department), he served as the chief ministerial spokesman in the [House of Lords](/House_of_Lords), effectively becoming the King’s primary minister. His influence was considerable, guiding foreign policy and domestic strategy.

In the [House of Commons](/House_of_Commons_of_Great_Britain), the initial leader of the Whig ministry was **[James Stanhope](/James_Stanhope,_1st_Earl_Stanhope)**, then [Secretary of State for the Southern Department](/Secretary_of_State_for_the_Southern_Department). Stanhope was a capable military man and diplomat, but the political arena of the Commons was a different beast. During the very first session of this Parliament, Stanhope found himself somewhat eclipsed by a rising star: **[Robert Walpole](/Robert_Walpole)**. Walpole, a shrewd and ambitious politician, began as the [Paymaster-general](/Paymaster-general) and also happened to be the brother-in-law of Viscount Townshend, a familial connection that certainly didn't hinder his ascent. His financial acumen and parliamentary skills quickly made him indispensable. By October 1715, a mere seven months into the Parliament's term, Walpole's undeniable talent and strategic positioning saw him promoted to the immensely powerful post of [First Lord of the Treasury](/First_Lord_of_the_Treasury), a clear indicator of his growing influence and a prelude to his eventual, legendary dominance in British politics.

## Replacement in Party Leadership by Sunderland and Stanhope

The rapid ascendancy of Townshend and Walpole, while effective, inevitably bred resentment and discontent within the Whig party itself. Power, after all, is a finite resource, and ambitious men rarely share it gracefully. By early 1717, the internal machinations and rivalries had reached a boiling point, leading to a significant reshuffle. Both Townshend and Walpole were, perhaps predictably, forced out of their prominent positions. Such is the ephemeral nature of political favour.

Townshend was succeeded by **[Lord Sunderland](/Charles_Spencer,_3rd_Earl_of_Sunderland)**, a figure of considerable aristocratic lineage and political cunning. Sunderland was not merely a replacement but an accumulation of power, also holding the title of Lord President of the Council. His influence solidified further when, in March 1718, he became [First Lord of the Treasury](/First_Lord_of_the_Treasury). This effectively consolidated his position to that of a de facto [Prime Minister](/Prime_Minister_of_the_United_Kingdom), though the term itself was not yet in common usage. For the subsequent three years, [George I](/George_I_of_Great_Britain)'s ministry found itself under the joint leadership of [Lord Sunderland](/Charles_Spencer,_3rd_Earl_of_Sunderland) and [James Stanhope](/James_Stanhope,_1st_Earl_Stanhope), who had managed to retain his position and re-establish his standing. Meanwhile, the recently ousted Townshend and Walpole were relegated to the unenviable position of opposition, biding their time and observing the unfolding drama from the sidelines.

## South Sea Bubble and Restoration in Power of Townshend and Walpole

The political fortunes of individuals are often dictated by external events, and few events were as catastrophic and politically destabilizing as the **[South Sea Bubble](/South_Sea_Bubble)**. This speculative economic frenzy, which gripped Britain in 1720, saw the shares of the [South Sea Company](/South_Sea_Company) surge to unsustainable heights before collapsing dramatically, ruining countless investors and shaking the financial foundations of the nation. The crisis exposed widespread corruption and incompetence, leading to a public outcry that demanded accountability.

By 1721, the political landscape had been irrevocably altered by the fallout. [Lord Sunderland](/Charles_Spencer,_3rd_Earl_of_Sunderland), heavily implicated in the scandal, found his political career in tatters. Though he managed to avoid impeachment, his authority was irrevocably damaged, and he had retreated to the [House of Lords](/House_of_Lords), his influence waning. Adding to the upheaval, [James Stanhope](/James_Stanhope,_1st_Earl_Stanhope), one of the joint leaders, tragically died in February 1721, a victim of the intense stress and political pressure of the era.

This confluence of disaster and sudden vacuum of power created the perfect opportunity for the previously sidelined figures. Both [Viscount Townshend](/Charles_Townshend,_2nd_Viscount_Townshend) and [Robert Walpole](/Robert_Walpole), who had largely kept their distance from the South Sea Company's more egregious dealings (or at least managed to appear to do so), were able to skillfully maneuver themselves back into power. Townshend returned as [Secretary of State](/Secretary_of_State_for_the_Northern_Department), while Walpole, with his reputation for financial acumen ironically bolstered by his relative detachment from the Bubble's collapse, replaced Sunderland as [First Lord of the Treasury](/First_Lord_of_the_Treasury). This marked the beginning of their formidable, if sometimes fraught, partnership that would dominate British politics for the next two decades, laying the foundations for the modern prime ministerial system. A prime example of how misfortune for some can be opportunity for others, provided one possesses the necessary ruthlessness and timing.

## Septennial Act

One of the most enduring, and perhaps self-serving, pieces of legislation enacted by this Parliament was the **[Septennial Act 1716](/Septennial_Act_1716)**. Passed before the first session even closed, this act fundamentally altered the rhythm of British politics by lengthening the maximum life of parliaments from three years to seven. The stated justification was to ensure greater stability, particularly in the wake of the [1715 Jacobite rising](/Jacobite_risings) and the perceived threat of continued unrest. Frequent elections, it was argued, contributed to instability and allowed for the disruptive influence of factions. However, the more cynical (and often correct) interpretation suggests it was a calculated move by the dominant Whigs to cement their power, granting them a longer period in office without the immediate pressure of facing the electorate. It certainly reduced the frequency of costly and often tumultuous general elections.

Another notable, though ultimately unsuccessful, legislative effort occurred in 1719, when an attempt to restrict the royal prerogative to create peers was decisively defeated. This proposal, often referred to as the Peerage Bill, aimed to limit the King's ability to create new peerages, thereby capping the size of the [House of Lords](/House_of_Lords) and preventing a monarch or government from swamping the upper chamber with their supporters. Its failure ensured that the Crown, and by extension the government, retained a crucial mechanism for influencing the balance of power within Parliament.

## Notable Acts of the Parliament

Beyond the grand political narratives, this Parliament also passed a series of acts that shaped the legal and social fabric of Great Britain. A truly diverse collection, demonstrating the wide, if sometimes mundane, reach of legislative power:

*   **[Riot Act](/Riot_Act) 1714**: A rather infamous piece of legislation, giving magistrates the power to declare an area in a state of riot and order the dispersal of crowds. Failure to disperse after the "reading of the Riot Act" could lead to severe penalties, including death. A clear demonstration of the state's intent to suppress popular dissent, particularly in the turbulent aftermath of the Hanoverian succession and Jacobite unrest.
*   **[Queen Anne's Bounty Act 1714](/Queen_Anne%27s_Bounty_Act_1714)**: Further regulating the fund established by Queen Anne to augment the incomes of poor clergy. A small act of benevolence in a sea of political maneuvering.
*   **[Schism Act 1714](/Schism_Act_1714)**: This act, originally passed under Queen Anne, aimed to prevent Dissenters (non-Anglican Protestants) from teaching in schools. Its existence reflects the ongoing religious tensions of the era, though it was largely repealed or made ineffective during this Parliament's tenure, showcasing the Whig government's more tolerant (or at least politically pragmatic) approach to religious minorities, as they often found common cause against the Tories.
*   **[Security of the Sovereign Act 1714](/Security_of_the_Sovereign_Act_1714)**: An act designed to shore up the position of the new Hanoverian monarch, making it treason to deny the King's title or to support the claims of the Pretender. A necessary legal weapon against Jacobite sympathizers.
*   **[Attainder of Duke of Ormonde Act 1714](/Attainder_of_Duke_of_Ormonde_Act_1714)**: The Duke of Ormonde, a prominent Tory and suspected Jacobite, was attainted, meaning he was declared a traitor and stripped of his lands and titles. This was part of the Whig government's broader crackdown on perceived enemies of the Hanoverian succession.
*   **[Building of Churches, London and Westminster Act 1714](/Building_of_Churches,_London_and_Westminster_Act_1714)**: Continuing the initiative to build fifty new churches in London and Westminster, a testament to civic development and religious infrastructure, or perhaps just a way to keep builders employed.
*   **[Septennial Act 1715](/Septennial_Act_1715)**: The seminal act discussed above, extending parliamentary terms. A truly self-serving masterpiece of legislation.
*   **[Papists Act 1715](/Papists_Act_1715)**: Reflecting continuing anti-Catholic sentiment, this act imposed further restrictions on Roman Catholics, particularly concerning their property and political rights, reinforcing the Protestant nature of the British state.
*   **[Bank of England Act 1716](/Bank_of_England_Act_1716)**: Further solidifying the role and powers of the [Bank of England](/Bank_of_England), a crucial institution for national finance and economic stability, particularly after the financial strains of war.
*   **[Queen Anne's Bounty Act 1716](/Queen_Anne%27s_Bounty_Act_1716)**: Another iteration, further refining the administration of the fund for poorer clergy.
*   **[Papists Act 1716](/Papists_Act_1716)**: More measures targeting Catholics, demonstrating the persistent fear and suspicion of a Catholic threat to the Protestant establishment.
*   **[Transportation Act 1717](/Transportation_Act_1717)**: A significant act that formalized and expanded the practice of transporting convicted criminals to the American colonies as a form of punishment. This provided a cheap source of labor for the colonies and a convenient way for Britain to clear its jails.
*   **[Indemnity Act 1717](/Indemnity_Act_1717)**: Often passed periodically, these acts offered pardons to those who had failed to take certain oaths or qualify for office, usually aimed at easing tensions and allowing dissenters to participate in public life without fear of prosecution.
*   **[Religious Worship Act 1718](/Religious_Worship_Act_1718)**: Further legislation impacting religious practices, likely aimed at clarifying or adjusting previous acts relating to non-conformist worship.
*   **[Corporations Act 1718](/Corporations_Act_1718)**: Dealing with the regulation and governance of various corporations, a crucial aspect of the burgeoning commercial and industrial landscape.
*   **[Adulteration of Coffee Act 1718](/Adulteration_of_Coffee_Act_1718)**: A rather specific act, aimed at preventing the fraudulent mixing of other substances with coffee. Even in the early 18th century, consumer protection was, occasionally, a concern. Or perhaps it was just about protecting tax revenues.
*   **[Dependency of Ireland on Great Britain Act 1719](/Dependency_of_Ireland_on_Great_Britain_Act_1719)**: Also known as the Declaratory Act for Ireland, this act explicitly affirmed the British Parliament's right to legislate for Ireland and asserted the British [House of Lords](/House_of_Lords)'s appellate jurisdiction over Irish courts. A clear assertion of imperial power over a subordinate kingdom, a move that would, predictably, fuel Irish resentment for generations.
*   **[Royal Exchange and London Assurance Corporation Act 1719](/Bubble_Act)** (aka Bubble Act): While officially named for specific corporations, this act became infamously known as the [Bubble Act](/Bubble_Act). Passed in response to the proliferation of dubious joint-stock companies, it aimed to curb speculative schemes by requiring a royal charter for companies to trade with transferable shares. Ironically, it was passed just *before* the South Sea Bubble burst, and its provisions were often circumvented or simply insufficient to prevent the ensuing financial catastrophe, though it did attempt to regulate the wilder excesses of early capitalism.

